    {"id":"empty-detail","type":"text","text":"## The empty AORs\n\nThe collection contains:\n\n- ==Zero== reports from SOUTHCOM\n- ==Zero== reports from NORTHCOM (CONUS LiDAR case is a civilian/FBI channel, not a COCOM ISR report)\n- ==Very few== from AFRICOM (Djibouti only)\n- ==Zero== from EUCOM proper, excluding the Mediterranean coast worked by CENTCOM-tasked patrols\n\nUAP are reported globally in non-government channels, so absence here is an artifact of ==where U.S. military sensors and reporting mandates are==, not where objects appear.","x":760,"y":160,"width":480,"height":480,"color":"6"},
    {"id":"aaro","type":"file","file":"99 - Reference/AARO Overview.md","x":760,"y":700,"width":480,"height":200,"color":"4"},
    {"id":"implication","type":"text","text":"## Implication\n\nWhen evaluating any AARO-era public statistic about UAP geography, ==always control for sensor density==.\n\nThe reported geography is the sensor geography. A rising INDOPACOM share is evidence of new sensors and reporting, not of objects relocating to the Pacific.\n\nConfidence: HIGH (structural sampling-bias argument, supported by the asymmetric distribution of the corpus).","x":760,"y":960,"width":480,"height":340,"color":"6"}
